# agent-chat .env for the robrix2 demo on LOCAL PALPO (plain-text, no rich UI)
# Copy the relevant lines into  /Users/zhangalex/Work/Projects/consult/agent-chat/.env
# Start from agent-chat/.env.example and override the Matrix block with these.
#
# WHICH VALUES YOU INVENT vs LOOK UP:
#   - API_TOKEN ................ INVENT any non-empty string (backend refuses to
#                                start if empty). NOT an LLM key. Local demo: any.
#   - MATRIX_BOT_PASSWORD ...... INVENT a password for the @agent-bridge account.
#   - MATRIX_AGENT_PASSWORD_SECRET  INVENT a long random string; agent passwords
#                                are derived = sha256("<secret>:<agentname>").
#   - MATRIX_BRIDGE_SECRET ..... OPTIONAL locally (leave blank). Only set if you
#                                want the bridge↔backend secret enforced.
#   - MATRIX_HOMESERVER / _SERVER_NAME  LOOK UP from Palpo (already filled below).
# Generate randoms with:  openssl rand -hex 24

# ── Backend ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# REQUIRED non-empty: backend-v2.js fails fast without it (README §"fail fast").
# Localhost callers are bearer-exempt at runtime, but the value must still be set.
API_TOKEN=dev-token-change-me
AGENT_CHAT_BACKEND_PORT=8090
# Message permalink base for Matrix "formatted" links (the 🔗 line the bridge appends).
# Without this the bridge falls back to the placeholder https://agent.example.com/msg,
# which doesn't resolve → robrix2 shows a broken/blank link-preview card. The /msg/:id
# page is served by the BACKEND (:8090), not the :8084 Agent Monitor — so point here, +/msg.
# (Do NOT use AGENT_CHAT_WEB_URL for this: it also drives the :8084 dashboard queue URL.)
MSG_BASE_URL=http://127.0.0.1:8090/msg

# OPTIONAL locally: shared secret the bridge sends as X-Bridge-Secret on
# POST /api/groups (used by `!mkgroup`). When BLANK, the backend SKIPS the check
# (createRequireBridgeSecret) and 127.0.0.1 is bearer-exempt — so a local demo
# works with this empty. Read by both sides as process.env.MATRIX_BRIDGE_SECRET
# (bridge-matrix.js:845, backend lib/backend/auth-adapter.js:235). Not in .env.example.
MATRIX_BRIDGE_SECRET=

# ── Matrix / Palpo ────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# Palpo CS-API. (Container listens on 0.0.0.0:8008; compose publishes it as :8128.)
# compose maps "8128:8008"; server_name = well_known.client = "127.0.0.1:8128".
# Host-side everything is :8128. Verified reachable under OrbStack docker.
MATRIX_HOMESERVER=http://127.0.0.1:8128
# Palpo server_name = the domain part of every MXID (@user:127.0.0.1:8128).
MATRIX_SERVER_NAME=127.0.0.1:8128

# The bridge bot account. INVENT the password. Pre-create the account with
# ./register-accounts.mjs (the bridge logs in; it won't self-register here —
# see MATRIX_REG_TOKEN note below).
MATRIX_BOT_USERNAME=agent-bridge
MATRIX_BOT_PASSWORD=

# Agent accounts become @ac_<name>:127.0.0.1:8128. Their passwords are derived:
#   sha256("${MATRIX_AGENT_PASSWORD_SECRET}:<agentname>")
# INVENT this secret (keep it stable so agents can log in again later):
MATRIX_AGENT_PASSWORD_SECRET=
MATRIX_AGENT_PREFIX=ac_

# Per-agent token enforcement. .env.example defaults to `hard`, which makes the
# backend reject an agent's own check_inbox with 403 ("agent token required") and
# refuse its MCP process registration ("missing MCP process") — so agents stay
# stuck at the Claude Code start screen and never see [NOTIFICATION]. For a local
# demo use `audit` (log-only, always allows). Verified necessary.
AGENTCHAT_AGENT_TOKEN_MODE=audit

# Leave BLANK. Your Palpo registers via the m.login.dummy flow (verified), but
# agent-chat's bridge auto-register ONLY does the m.login.registration_token flow
# (bridge-matrix.js matrixRegister throws without a token). So we DON'T rely on
# the bridge to register: run ./register-accounts.mjs first (dummy flow), then the
# bridge just LOGS IN (matrixLogin) and never touches its register path.
MATRIX_REG_TOKEN=

# ── Trust gate ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# 'audit' = bot/agents accept invites and just log trust (simplest for a demo).
# Switch to 'enforce' for safety and whitelist your robrix2 user as inviter.
MATRIX_TRUST_MODE=audit
# MATRIX_TRUST_MODE=enforce
# MATRIX_TRUSTED_INVITER_MXIDS=@<your-robrix-user>:127.0.0.1:8128

# ── Notes ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# Port sanity (verified live, OrbStack docker): compose maps 8128:8008,
# server_name=127.0.0.1:8128, well_known.client=http://127.0.0.1:8128. Host-side
# everything is :8128; /_matrix/client/versions responds. Run ./preflight.sh to
# re-confirm CS-API + MXID domain + login before the demo.
#
# The bridge here runs as a local node process (start-demo.sh) on the host, so
# 127.0.0.1:8128 reaches Palpo via OrbStack's published port. Only if you ran the
# bridge INSIDE a container would you need host.docker.internal instead.
